segments.text: All right, so this morning I am going to provide some background on food delivery services in Seattle and also provide a summary of proposed legislation that is co-sponsored by
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Councilmember Peterson and Councilmember Strauss that would permanently cap delivery service fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The policy objective of the legislation would be to require food delivery platforms to engage in agreed upon reasonable and transparent business transactions when operating in Seattle to protect the interest of consumers and restaurants.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And the way to achieve that goal would be to
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: amend existing regulations on food delivery platforms, and that is SMC 7.30.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: As a reminder, right now food delivery platforms are required to enter into an agreement with restaurants before the food delivery platform offers pickup and delivery services.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Background on food delivery services is that consumer demand for food delivery services is steadily growing.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: As a public commenter noted that
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: growing demand started pre-pandemic, but it did sharply accelerate during the pandemic.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Food delivery platforms charge up to 30% or more for their delivery services.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Although many restaurants are interested in providing delivery to their consumers and to their customers, if they are not able to provide those services in-house because they don't have labor capacity, then food delivery platforms help to bridge that gap so that they can provide that service.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Restaurants do have narrow profit margins of 10% or lower, with full service restaurants having even more narrow profit margins of around 3% to 5%.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: So if food delivery platforms are charging up to 30% or more, restaurants have narrow profit margins.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: You can do the math and understand that high fees can equal drastically reduced profits.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: As restaurants are increasingly relying on food delivery and customers
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: expect this kind of service, it can add to struggles to stay in business for restaurants.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And also, as noted in public comment, there are about three major companies who are operating in the country for providing food delivery services.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And because of this marketplace dominance, restaurants do have limited bargaining power to negotiate different fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: As I mentioned, the use of delivery services did sharply accelerate during the pandemic.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And noting the impact of these high delivery fees on companies, the mayor issued a civil emergency order in April of 2020 that capped all fees for platform delivery services at 15%.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: A number of months thereafter, the Washington governor issued a
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: proclamation for across the state to have a 15% on just delivery fees cap and then an 18% cap on all platform fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Across the country, there were numerous cities that were in states that had these emergency orders capping delivery service fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: In June of last year, the governor rescinded the state proclamation in anticipation of easing restrictions on in-house dining that happened later that month.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Presently, the mayor's civil emergency order is still in place, but it will expire upon the impending termination of the civil emergency.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Trends in recent developments is, as I said earlier, just some statistics on how food delivery platform services have grown from pre-pandemic through now, and similar growth is expected through 2026.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Food delivery platforms are becoming a standard business operation with 77% of restaurants, this is national data, offering services through these platforms and business resulting from these platforms facilitating delivery is 21 to 30% of current restaurant sales.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Recognizing the need to address these problems, four cities have enacted laws that permanently cap delivery service fees,
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Minneapolis, New York City, Philadelphia, and San Francisco.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: I understand that Portland is also considering a permanent cap on delivery service fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: This legislation would permanently cap delivery service fees.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: It is similar to the emergency order, but does have some unique provisions.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: The first is that it would clarify that there must be an agreement between a food delivery platform and a restaurant for any fees related to delivery services.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: There is mutual consent, there are no surprises.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Next, food delivery platforms would be required to provide delivery services for no more than 15% of the purchase price of each order.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: What is different about this permanent cap is that there would be an option for restaurants to opt out of the fee limitations and pay higher fees for additional services.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: There would be conditions
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: for that opt out to pass legal muster.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Food delivery platforms would need to offer a service package option that includes delivery services for no more than 50%.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: So there would always be an options for restaurants to pay no more than 15% for delivery.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: Food delivery platforms would need to provide this option without penalty to the restaurant within 30 days of the restaurant's written request for it.
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09

segments.text: And then restaurants would
segments.speaker: SPEAKER_09
